{"title_page": "Charles Perkins (Aboriginal activist)", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian Aboriginal activist and football player, coach and administrator}}\n{{About|the Australian Aboriginal sports figure and activist|other persons with this name|Charles Perkins (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2011}}\n{{lead too short|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Charles Perkins\n| image        = CharlesPerkinsGraduate01.jpg\n| image_size   =\n| alt          =\n| caption      = Charles Perkins, approx 1965, first [[Australian Aborigine|Aboriginal Australian]] to graduate from the [[University of Sydney]].\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date|df=y|1936|06|16}}<ref name=\"Read_2001\">{{cite book | title=Charles Perkins: a biography | publisher=Penguin Books | last=Read | first=Peter | year=2001 | location=Ringwood, Victoria | page=351 | isbn=0-14-100688-9}}</ref>\n|birth_place   = [[Alice Springs]], [[Northern Territory]], Australia\n|death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=y|2000|10|19|1936|06|16}}\n|death_place   = [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n|nationality   = Australian\n|other_names   = Charlie Perkins, Kumantjayi Perkins\n|known_for     = Activism, Public Service, Sport\n|education     = [[Bachelor of Arts]]\n|alma_mater    = [[University of Sydney]]\n|spouse        = Eileen Munchenberg\n|children      = [[Hetti Perkins|Hetti]], [[Rachel Perkins|Rachel]] and Adam\n| module      = {{Infobox football biography|embed=yes\n| name = Charles Perkins| image =\n| height =\n| position =\n| youthyears1=\n| youthclubs1=\n| years1 = 1950 | years2 = 1954\u20131955 | years3 = 1956\u20131957 | years4 = 1957 | years5 = 1957 | years6 = 1957\u20131959 | years7 = 1959\u20131960 | years8 = 1961\u20131964 | years9 =?\u20131969\n| clubs1 = [[Port Adelaide Pirates SC|Port Thistle]] | clubs2 = International United | clubs3 = Fiorentina | clubs4 = Budapest | clubs5 = [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] | clubs6 = [[Bishop Auckland F.C.|Bishop Auckland]] | clubs7 = [[Adelaide Raiders|Adelaide Croatia]] | clubs8 = [[Sydney Olympic|Pan-Hellenic]] | clubs9 =Bankstown\n| caps1 = ? | goals1 = | caps2 = ? | goals2 = | caps3 = ? | goals3 = | caps4 = ? | goals4 = | caps5 = 0 | goals5 = 0 | caps6 = ? | goals6 = | caps7 = ? | goals7 = | caps8 = ? | goals8 = | caps9 = ? | goals9 =\n| manageryears1 = 1959\u20131960 | manageryears2 =1961\u20131964\n| managerclubs1 = [[Adelaide Raiders|Adelaide Croatia]] | managerclubs2 =[[Sydney Olympic|Pan-Hellenic]]\n| nationalyears1=\n| nationalteam1=\n| nationalcaps1= | nationalgoals1 = | pcupdate = 15 December 2008| ntupdate =\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Charles Nelson Perkins''', [[Order of Australia|AO]],<ref name=\"Order\">{{Cite It's an Honour |ausawardid=872479|date=26 January 1987 |recipient=PERKINS, Charles Nelson |award=Officer of the Order of Australia |postnominal=AO |citation=AO AD 87. FOR SERVICE TO ABORIGINAL WELFARE|accessdate=9 March 2015 }}</ref> commonly known as '''Charlie Perkins''' (16 June 1936 \u2013 19 October 2000<ref>{{cite book | title=A Bastard like me | publisher=Ure Smith | last=Perkins | first=Charles | year=1975 | location=Sydney | page=199 | isbn=0-7254-0256-3}}</ref>), was an [[Australian Aborigine|Australian Aboriginal]] activist, [[association football|soccer]] player and administrator.\n\n==Early life and family==\nPerkins was born in [[Alice Springs]], originally from nearby [[Arltunga]], to [[Hetty Perkins]] and Martin Connelly, originally from [[Mount Isa]], [[Queensland]]. His mother was born to a white father and an [[Arrernte people|Arrernte]] mother, while his father was born to an Irish father and a [[Kalkadoon]] mother. Perkins had one full sibling and nine other half-siblings by his mother, and was also a cousin of artist and [[football (soccer)|soccer]] player [[John Kundereri Moriarty|John Moriarty]].{{cn|date=August 2018}} He was the great-uncle of [[Pat Turner (Aboriginal activist)|Pat Turner]], and inspired her work to improve the lives of and right to self-determination for indigenous people.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Henningham |first1=Nikki |title=Turner, Patricia |url=http://www.womenaustralia.info/leaders/biogs/WLE0239b.htm |website=The Encyclopedia of Women and Leadership in Twentieth-Century Australia |publisher=Australian Research Council |accessdate=15 August 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180420094324/http://www.womenaustralia.info/leaders/biogs/WLE0239b.htm |archivedate=20 April 2018 |location=Canberra, Australia |date=27 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1952 and 1957, Perkins worked as an apprentice [[fitter and turner]] for the British Tube Mills company in Adelaide.<ref name=\"NLA\" />\n\nHe married Eileen Munchenberg, a descendant of a German Lutheran family, on 23 September 1961 and had two daughters ([[Hetti Perkins |Hetti]] and [[Rachel Perkins|Rachel]]), and a son (Adam).<ref name=\"NLA\">{{cite web | url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.ms-ms8047 | title=Papers of Charles Perkins (1936\u20132000) | publisher=[[National Library of Australia]] | date=April 2002 | accessdate=20 January 2007}}</ref> His granddaughter through Hetti is actress [[Madeleine Madden]].\n\n== Education ==\nHe was educated at St Mary's Church School in Alice Springs, [[St Francis House]] for Aboriginal Boys in [[Adelaide]], the Metropolitan Business College, [[Sydney]] and the [[University of Sydney]] from where he graduated in 1966 with a [[Bachelor of Arts]]. He was the first Aboriginal man in Australia to graduate from university. While at university he worked part-time for the [[City of South Sydney]] cleaning toilets.<ref name=\"Perkins3\">{{cite interview | date=5 May 1939\n | last=Perkins | first=Charles| interviewer=Robin Hughes |title=Charles Perkins - Tape 3| work=Australian Biography|quote=I used to clean the toilets, down at South Sydney, and I used to do such a good job they said, 'Why don't you take this on full time?' I used to make them sparkle - all the public toilets around the place, and the one at South Sydney Depot, right down Redfern. And I used to clean them, I had no problem. Any job is a good job. And ah, you know if anybody else can do it I can do it.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://sydney.edu.au/perkins/about/charles_perkins.shtml | title=Charles Perkins | publisher=University of Sydney | accessdate=18 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Public life==\n\n===The Freedom Ride===\n\nIn 1965 he was one of the key members of the [[Freedom Ride (Australia)|Freedom Ride]] \u2013 a bus tour through New South Wales by activists protesting discrimination against Aboriginal people in small towns in NSW, Australia. This action was inspired by the [[United States of America|US]] [[Civil Rights]] [[Freedom Ride]] campaign in 1961. The Australian Freedom Ride aimed to expose discrepancies in living, education and health conditions among the Aboriginal population. The tour targeted rural towns such as [[Walgett]], [[Moree, New South Wales|Moree]], and [[Kempsey, New South Wales|Kempsey]]. They acted to publicise acts of blatant discrimination. This was demonstrated through one of the Freedom Ride activities in Walgett. A local [[Returned and Services League of Australia|RSL]] club refused entry to Aborigines, including those who were ex-servicemen who participated in the two [[World Wars]]. At one stage during the Rides, the protesters' bus was run off the road.\n\nOn 20 February 1965, Perkins and his party tried to enter the swimming pool at [[Moree, New South Wales|Moree]], where the [[Moree Plains Shire|local council]] had barred Aboriginal people from swimming since its opening 40 years earlier. They stood at the gate refusing to let anyone else in if they were not let in. In response to this action, the riders faced physical opposition from several hundred local white Australians, including community leaders, and were pelted with eggs and tomatoes. These events were broadcast across Australia, and under pressure from public opinion, the council eventually reversed the ban on Aboriginal swimmers. The Freedom Ride then moved on, but on the way out they were followed by a line of cars, one of which collided with the rear of their bus forcing them to return to Moree where they found that the council had reneged on their previous decision. The Freedom Riders protested once again, forcing the council to  remove the ban once more.<ref name=Cockerill>{{cite web\n  | last =Cockerill\n  | first =Michael\n  | title =Australian football loses a trail-blazer\n  | publisher =[[FIFA]]\n  | date =20 April 2001\n  | url =http://images.fifa.com/en/organisation/index/0,1521,24227,00.html?articleid=24227\n  | accessdate =20 January 2007\n  | url-status =dead\n  | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20070312173606/http://images.fifa.com/en/organisation/index/0%2C1521%2C24227%2C00.html?articleid=24227\n  | archivedate =12 March 2007\n  | df =dmy-all\n  }}</ref>\n\nOn 6 August 1965, Charles Perkins staged a fake \"kidnapping\" of 5 year old Nancy Prasad from under the nose of immigration officials at the Sydney airport for the purpose of highlighting the injustice her deportation under Australia's \"White Australia\" immigration policy.<ref>{{ cite web|title=Immigration Nation: Part 3 | url =https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-WNRb8Hypjo }}</ref><ref name=telegraph-nancyprasad>{{cite news| url = http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/deported-nancy-prasad-was-the-little-girl-who-helped-bring-down-the-white-australia-policy/news-story/001ee3eff23d0cef94d0961e2811396a|title=Deported: Nancy Prasad was the little girl who helped bring down the White Australia policy|author=Benns, Matthew|work=Daily Telegraph|date=7 August 2015|access-date=16 December 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{ cite book|title =Deported: A History of Forced Departures from Australia  | first1 =Glenn|last1=Nicholls| url=https://books.google.com/?id=dRQcNtT35AIC&pg=PA113&dq=nancy+prasad#v=onepage&q=nancy%20prasad&f=false | isbn =9780868409894| year =2007}}</ref>  His antic had effect.  The newspapers headlined the \"kidnapping\".  Even so, 5 year old Nancy Prasad was taken to the airport again, and deported to Fiji on 7 August 1965.<ref name=telegraph-nancyprasad/>\n\n===1967 Referendum===\n{{See also|Australian referendum, 1967 (Aboriginals)}}\nIn 1967 a [[referendum]] was held on [[Australian Constitution|constitutional amendments]] to allow the inclusion of Aboriginal people in censuses and giving the [[Parliament of Australia]] the right to introduce legislation specifically for Aboriginal people. In the lead up to the referendum Perkins was manager of the Foundation for Aboriginal Affairs, an organization that took a key role in advocating a Yes vote. The constitutional amendment passed with a 90.77% majority.\n\n===Public service===\nIn 1969 Perkins began his career in public service as a Senior Research Officer with the Office of Aboriginal Affairs. In 1972, as a public servant, he was suspended for alleged improper conduct after he called the [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]]\u2013[[National Party of Australia|Country]] Coalition government in [[Western Australia]] 'racist and [[Redneck (stereotype)|redneck]]'.\n\nIn 1981, he was appointed Permanent Secretary of the [[Department of Aboriginal Affairs]], the first Aboriginal to become a permanent head of a federal government department. He served as Chairman of the Aboriginal Development Commission between 1981 and 1984. Throughout his career he was a strident critic of [[Government of Australia|Australian Government]] policies on indigenous affairs and was renowned for his fiery comments. [[Prime Minister of Australia|Prime Minister]] [[Bob Hawke]] once said of Perkins that he \"sometimes found it difficult to observe the constraints usually imposed on permanent heads of departments because he had a burning passion for advancing the interests of his people\". Perkins served as Secretary until 1988. A year later he became Chairman of the [[Arrernte Council]] of Central Australia.\n\nIn 1993 Perkins was elected commissioner of the [[Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Commission]] for an area of the central Northern Territory. In 1994, he was elected Deputy Chairperson of ATSIC.\n\n===Public commentary===\nOn 7 April 2000, Perkins suggested that 'Sydney will burn during the [Sydney 2000] Olympics.' The comment sparked outrage from many quarters.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.eniar.org/news/perkins.html | title=Charles Perkins \u2013 Obituary | publisher=The Times Magazine | work=[[The Times]] | date=20 August 2000 | accessdate=19 July 2008 | via=European Network for Indigenous Australian Rights | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421062414/http://www.eniar.org/news/perkins.html | archivedate=21 April 2012}}</ref> In May 2000 Perkins declared that the [[Australian Football League]] and the [[Australian Rugby League]] were racist, suggesting that the AFL \"acts in a racist manner at the highest level.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-26756419.html | title=AFL: Charles Perkins brands AFL and ARL as racist | date=24 May 2000 | agency=[[Australian Associated Press|AAP]] | accessdate=17 December 2008}}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n== Soccer career ==\nPerkins began playing in 1950 with Adelaide team the Yeeters [[Port Adelaide Pirates|Port Thistle]]. In 1951 he was selected for a [[South Australia]] under 18 representative team. He went on to play for a number of teams in Adelaide including International United (1954\u201355), Budapest (1956\u201357) and Fiorentina (1957).\n\nIn 1957 he was invited to trial with [[Football League First Division|English first division]] team [[Liverpool F.C.]]. Perkins ended up trialling and training with Liverpool's city rival [[Everton FC]]. While at Everton Perkins had a physical confrontation with the Everton reserve grade manager after being called a \"kangaroo bastard.\" After this incident, Perkins left Everton FC to move to Wigan where he worked as a coal miner at the [[Mosley Common]] Colliery alongside [[Great Britain national rugby league team|Great Britain]] [[rugby league]] player [[Terry O'Grady]]. Perkins played two seasons for leading English amateur team [[Bishop Auckland F.C.]] between 1957 and 1959.\nPerkins in mid-1959 decided to return to Australia after trialling with [[Manchester United]].<ref name=\"NLA\" />\n\nOn returning to Australia Perkins was appointed captain/coach of [[Adelaide Raiders|Adelaide Croatia]]. At Croatia he played alongside notable Aboriginal figures [[Gordon Briscoe]] and [[John Kundereri Moriarty|John Moriarty]].<ref name=\"Perkins\">{{cite interview | date=5 May 1998 | last=Perkins | first=Charles| interviewer=Robin Hughes |title=Charles Perkins - Tape2| work=Australian Biography}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=The Australian People: An Encyclopedia of the Nation, Its People and Their Origins | publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] | last=Jupp | first=James | year=2001 | page=248 | isbn=0-521-80789-1}}</ref>\n\nIn 1961 when Perkins moved to Sydney to study at university he played with Pan-Hellenic (later known as [[Sydney Olympic FC]]) in the New South Wales State League where he became captain/coach. He later played for Bankstown and retired in 1965.\n\nHe later served as president of former [[National Soccer League]] team [[Canberra City SC|Canberra City]].  He was appointed Australian Soccer Federation (a forerunner of the [[Football Federation Australia]]) vice-president in 1987 and was the chairman of the Australian Indoor Soccer Federation (later known as the Australian Futsal Federation) for ten years until his death in [[Sydney]] in 2000.<ref name=Cockerill /><ref name=Perkins />\n\n==Awards and honours==\nPerkins was awarded Jaycees Young Man of the Year in 1966, [[NAIDOC]] Aboriginal of the Year in 1993 and an [[Officer of the Order of Australia]] in 1987.<ref name=Order/> Perkins was inducted into the [[Football Federation Australia Football Hall of Fame]] for services as a player, coach and administrator in 2000. In 1998 Perkins was awarded an [[honorary doctorate]] of letters by the [[University of Western Sydney]]. Shortly before his death he was awarded an honorary doctorate of law by the University of Sydney. Perkins was named by the [[National Trust of Australia]] as one of [[Australian National Living Treasures|Australia's Living National Treasures]].\n\nIn 2001 The Dr Charles Perkins AO Memorial Oration and Dr Charles Perkins AO Memorial Prize were established in his honour by the University of Sydney.  In 2009 The Charlie Perkins Trust instituted two scholarships per year to allow Indigenous Australians to study for up to three years at the [[University of Oxford]].<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/10/22/2721161.htm Funding for Indigenous Oxford scholarships (ABC News)]</ref><ref name=\"FFA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.footballhalloffame.com.au/ |title=The Australian Football Hall of Fame |publisher=[[Football Federation Australia]] |accessdate=9 December 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110107102858/http://www.footballhalloffame.com.au/ |archivedate=7 January 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=\"Uni\">{{cite web | url=http://www.koori.usyd.edu.au/news/oration.shtml | title=Dr Charles Perkins AO Annual Memorial Oration and Prize | publisher=[[University of Sydney]] | accessdate=18 December 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"trust\">{{cite web | url=http://www.nsw.nationaltrust.org.au/treasureslist.html | title=List of Treasures | publisher=[[National Trust of Australia|National Trust]] | accessdate=18 December 2008 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070210145542/http://www.nsw.nationaltrust.org.au/treasureslist.html | archivedate=10 February 2007 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012 [[The University of Sydney]] Centre for Obesity, Diabetes and Cardiovascular Disease was renamed the [[Charles Perkins Centre]] in his recognition.\n\n==Film and documentary==\n* 1993: ''[[Blood Brothers (film series)|Freedom Ride]]'' by Rachel Perkins, Ned R Lander \u2013 Australia \u2013 55 minutes<ref name=movie>{{cite web|url=http://www.creativespirits.info/resources/movies/FreedomRide.html|title=Aboriginal resources > Movies > Freedom Ride|access-date=23 May 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091125033645/http://www.creativespirits.info/resources/movies/FreedomRide.html|archive-date=25 November 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 2009: ''[[Fire Talker]]''\n* 2009: ''[[Remembering Charlie Perkins]]''  56 minutes 38 seconds\n\n===''Freedom Ride''===\n''Freedom Ride'' is part of a four-episode documentary by Rachel Perkins and Ned Lander. It tells a chapter of Charles Perkins' life. The Freedom Ride was a busload of concerned white and black people, most of them university students, who visited several towns in rural and outback Australia to elevate public awareness of racial intolerance in Australia.<ref name=movie/>\n\n==='' Fire Talker: The Life and Times of Charlie Perkins''===\nThis film by [[Ivan Sen]] uses archival footage from the early 1960s to 2001 and builds an intimate and honest portrait of Perkins life bound inexorably with the most dramatic political shifts in Australian Indigenous policy.<ref name=\"Sydney Operahouse\">{{cite press release | url=http://www.sydneyoperahouse.com/About/09EventMediaRelease/MessageSticks.aspx | title=Message Sticks, Australia's only Indigenous film festival celebrates its 10th anniversary | publisher=Sydney Opera House | accessdate=9 March 2015 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327102258/http://www.sydneyoperahouse.com/About/09EventMediaRelease/MessageSticks.aspx | archivedate=27 March 2012 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===''Remembering Charlie Perkins''===\n2009 Charlie Perkins memorial oration, [[Gordon Briscoe]] recalls Perkins' fight for equality and liberty.<ref name=\"brisco\">{{cite episode | title=Gordon Briscoe Remembers His Friend Charlie Perkins | series=Big Ideas | network=[[ABC News 24]] | airdate=6 November 2009 | url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/bigideas/browse/video_popup.htm?vidURL=/tv/bigideas/stories/2009/11/06/2734926-mediarss-full.xml&vidTitle=Gordon%20Briscoe%20Remembers%20His%20Friend%20Charlie%20Perkins&vidLength=Full | access-date=28 June 2019 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402202533/http://www.abc.net.au/tv/bigideas/browse/video_popup.htm?vidURL=%2Ftv%2Fbigideas%2Fstories%2F2009%2F11%2F06%2F2734926-mediarss-full.xml&vidTitle=Gordon%20Briscoe%20Remembers%20His%20Friend%20Charlie%20Perkins&vidLength=Full | archivedate=2 April 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nPerkins died in Sydney on 19 October 2000 of [[renal failure]]. During the 1970s Perkins had a kidney transplant and at the time of his death was the longest post-transplant survivor in Australia.<ref name=\"NLA\" /><ref name=\"abc1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/pm/stories/s210963.htm|title=Hetty Perkins discusses kidney research fundraising|work=PM|publisher=ABC Radio|accessdate=8 October 2009}}</ref>  In the period immediately following his death, he was known as '''Kumantjayi Perkins''', Kumantjayi being a name used to refer to a deceased person in [[Arrernte people|Arrernte]] culture.<ref name=\"creative\">{{cite web | url=http://www.creativespirits.info/aboriginalculture/people/ | title=Should you name a dead Aboriginal person? | publisher=Creative Spirits, Jens Korff | accessdate=18 December 2008}}</ref> His body was returned to Alice Springs a week after his death.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading and external links==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book\n  | title =A Bastard like me\n  | last =Perkins\n  | first =Charles\n  | publisher =Ure Smith\n  | year =1975\n  | isbn =0-7254-0256-3 | location =Sydney\n  | authorlink =\n  }}\n*{{cite book\n  | title =Charles Perkins: a biography\n  | last =Read\n  | first =Peter\n  | publisher =Viking\n  | year =1990\n  | isbn =0-14-013280-5\n| location =Ringwood, Victoria\n  | authorlink =\n  }}\n*{{cite web\n |url=http://www.naa.gov.au/fsheets/fs225.html \n |title=Charles Nelson Perkins \n |date=July 2004 \n |publisher=[[National Archives of Australia]] \n |accessdate=20 January 2007 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060828174842/http://naa.gov.au/fsheets/fs225.html \n |archivedate=28 August 2006 \n |url-status=dead \n |df=dmy \n}}\n*{{cite web\n  | url =http://www.australianbiography.gov.au/subjects/perkins/\n  | title =Charles Perkins\n  | year =2004\n  | publisher =[[Government of Australia|Australian Government]]\n  | work =Australian Biography\n  | accessdate =  25 October 2010}}\n*Classroom resources on Charles Perkins: [http://dl.nfsa.gov.au/module/1026/ Institutions], [http://dl.nfsa.gov.au/module/1033/ Freedom Ride]\n*[http://www.perkinstrust.com.au/ The Charlie Perkins Trust for Children and Students]\n*[http://www.portrait.gov.au/people/charles-perkins-1936 Portraits of Charles Perkins] in the National Portrait Gallery \n{{refend}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{S-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Taylor (public servant)|John Taylor]] }}\n{{s-ttl|title= [[Departmental secretary|Secretary]] of the [[Department of Aboriginal Affairs]]| years   = 1984 \u2013 1988}}\n{{s-aft| after= [[Wilfred James \"Bill\" Gray|Bill Gray]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Football Federation Australia Hall of Fame}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perkins, Charles}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Alice Springs]]\n[[Category:Australian public servants]]\n[[Category:Australian soccer players]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate soccer players]]\n[[Category:Indigenous Australian soccer players]]\n[[Category:Football Federation Australia Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Australian soccer coaches]]\n[[Category:Sydney Olympic FC players]]\n[[Category:Kidney transplant recipients]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:Sydney Olympic FC managers]]\n[[Category:Australian indigenous rights activists]]\n[[Category:University of Sydney alumni]]\n[[Category:Arrernte]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Association footballers not categorized by position]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian Aboriginal activist and football player, coach and administrator}}\n{{About|the Australian Aboriginal sports figure and activist|other persons with this name|Charles Perkins (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2011}}\n{{lead too short|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Charles Perkins\n| image        = CharlesPerkinsGraduate01.jpg\n| image_size   =\n| alt          =\n| caption      = Charles Perkins, approx 1965, first [[Australian Aborigine|Aboriginal Australian]] to graduate from the [[University of Sydney]].\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date|df=y|1936|06|16}}<ref name=\"Read_2001\">{{cite book | title=Charles Perkins: a biography | publisher=Penguin Books | last=Read | first=Peter | year=2001 | location=Ringwood, Victoria | page=351 | isbn=0-14-100688-9}}</ref>\n|birth_place   = [[Alice Springs]], [[Northern Territory]], Australia\n|death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=y|2000|10|19|1936|06|16}}\n|death_place   = [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n|nationality   = Australian\n|other_names   = Charlie Perkins, Kumantjayi Perkins\n|known_for     = Activism, Public Service, Sport\n|education     = [[Bachelor of Arts]]\n|alma_mater    = [[University of Sydney]]\n|spouse        = Eileen Munchenberg\n|children      = [[Hetti Perkins|Hetti]], [[Rachel Perkins|Rachel]] and Adam\n| module      = {{Infobox football biography|embed=yes\n| name = Charles Perkins| image =\n| height =\n| position =\n| youthyears1=\n| youthclubs1=\n| years1 = 1950 | years2 = 1954\u20131955 | years3 = 1956\u20131957 | years4 = 1957 | years5 = 1957 | years6 = 1957\u20131959 | years7 = 1959\u20131960 | years8 = 1961\u20131964 | years9 =?\u20131969\n| clubs1 = [[Port Adelaide Pirates SC|Port Thistle]] | clubs2 = International United | clubs3 = Fiorentina | clubs4 = Budapest | clubs5 = [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] | clubs6 = [[Bishop Auckland F.C.|Bishop Auckland]] | clubs7 = [[Adelaide Raiders|Adelaide Croatia]] | clubs8 = [[Sydney Olympic|Pan-Hellenic]] | clubs9 =Bankstown\n| caps1 = ? | goals1 = | caps2 = ? | goals2 = | caps3 = ? | goals3 = | caps4 = ? | goals4 = | caps5 = 0 | goals5 = 0 | caps6 = ? | goals6 = | caps7 = ? | goals7 = | caps8 = ? | goals8 = | caps9 = ? | goals9 =\n| manageryears1 = 1959\u20131960 | manageryears2 =1961\u20131964\n| managerclubs1 = [[Adelaide Raiders|Adelaide Croatia]] | managerclubs2 =[[Sydney Olympic|Pan-Hellenic]]\n| nationalyears1=\n| nationalteam1=\n| nationalcaps1= | nationalgoals1 = | pcupdate = 15 December 2008| ntupdate =\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Charles Nelson Perkins''', [[Order of Australia|AO]],<ref name=\"Order\">{{Cite It's an Honour |ausawardid=872479|date=26 January 1987 |recipient=PERKINS, Charles Nelson |award=Officer of the Order of Australia |postnominal=AO |citation=AO AD 87. FOR SERVICE TO ABORIGINAL WELFARE|accessdate=9 March 2015 }}</ref> commonly known as '''Charlie Perkins''' (16 June 1936 \u2013 19 October 2000<ref>{{cite book | title=A Bastard like me | publisher=Ure Smith | last=Perkins | first=Charles | year=1975 | location=Sydney | page=199 | isbn=0-7254-0256-3}}</ref>), was an [[Australian Aborigine|Australian Aboriginal]] activist, [[association football|soccer]] player and administrator.\n\n==Early life and family==\nPerkins was born in [[Alice Springs]], originally from nearby [[Arltunga]], to [[Hetty Perkins]] and Martin Connelly, originally from [[Mount Isa]], [[Queensland]]. His mother was born to a white father and an [[Arrernte people|Arrernte]] mother, while his father was born to an Irish father and a [[Kalkadoon]] mother. Perkins had one full sibling and nine other half-siblings by his mother, and was also a cousin of artist and [[football (soccer)|soccer]] player [[John Kundereri Moriarty|John Moriarty]].{{cn|date=August 2018}} He was the great-uncle of [[Pat Turner (Aboriginal activist)|Pat Turner]], and inspired her work to improve the lives of and right to self-determination for indigenous people.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Henningham |first1=Nikki |title=Turner, Patricia |url=http://www.womenaustralia.info/leaders/biogs/WLE0239b.htm |website=The Encyclopedia of Women and Leadership in Twentieth-Century Australia |publisher=Australian Research Council |accessdate=15 August 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180420094324/http://www.womenaustralia.info/leaders/biogs/WLE0239b.htm |archivedate=20 April 2018 |location=Canberra, Australia |date=27 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1952 and 1957, Perkins worked as an apprentice [[fitter and turner]] for the British Tube Mills company in Adelaide.<ref name=\"NLA\" />\n\nHe married Eileen Munchenberg, a descendant of a German Lutheran family, on 23 September 1961 and had two daughters ([[Hetti Perkins |Hetti]] and [[Rachel Perkins|Rachel]]), and a son (Adam).<ref name=\"NLA\">{{cite web | url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.ms-ms8047 | title=Papers of Charles Perkins (1936\u20132000) | publisher=[[National Library of Australia]] | date=April 2002 | accessdate=20 January 2007}}</ref> His granddaughter through Hetti is actress [[Madeleine Madden]].\n\n== Education ==\nHe was educated at St Mary's Church School in Alice Springs, [[St Francis House]] for Aboriginal Boys in [[Adelaide]], the Metropolitan Business College, [[Sydney]] and the [[University of Sydney]] from where he graduated in 1966 with a [[Bachelor of Arts]]. He was the first Aboriginal man in Australia to graduate from university. While at university he worked part-time for the [[City of South Sydney]] cleaning toilets.<ref name=\"Perkins3\">{{cite interview | date=5 May 1939\n | last=Perkins | first=Charles| interviewer=Robin Hughes |title=Charles Perkins - Tape 3| work=Australian Biography|quote=I used to clean the toilets, down at South Sydney, and I used to do such a good job they said, 'Why don't you take this on full time?' I used to make them sparkle - all the public toilets around the place, and the one at South Sydney Depot, right down Redfern. And I used to clean them, I had no problem. Any job is a good job. And ah, you know if anybody else can do it I can do it.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://sydney.edu.au/perkins/about/charles_perkins.shtml | title=Charles Perkins | publisher=University of Sydney | accessdate=18 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Public life==\n\n===The Freedom Ride===\n\nIn 1965 he was one of the key members of the [[Freedom Ride (Australia)|Freedom Ride]] \u2013 a bus tour through New South Wales by activists protesting discrimination against Aboriginal people in small towns in NSW, Australia. This action was inspired by the [[United States of America|US]] [[Civil Rights]] [[Freedom Ride]] campaign in 1961. The Australian Freedom Ride aimed to expose discrepancies in living, education and health conditions among the Aboriginal population. The tour targeted rural towns such as [[Walgett]], [[Moree, New South Wales|Moree]], and [[Kempsey, New South Wales|Kempsey]]. They acted to publicise acts of blatant discrimination. This was demonstrated through one of the Freedom Ride activities in Walgett. A local [[Returned and Services League of Australia|RSL]] club refused entry to Aborigines, including those who were ex-servicemen who participated in the two [[World Wars]]. At one stage during the Rides, the protesters' bus was run off the road.\n\nOn 20 February 1965, Perkins and his party tried to enter the swimming pool at [[Moree, New South Wales|Moree]], where the [[Moree Plains Shire|local council]] had barred Aboriginal people from swimming since its opening 40 years earlier. They stood at the gate refusing to let anyone else in if they were not let in. In response to this action, the riders faced physical opposition from several hundred local white Australians, including community leaders, and were pelted with eggs and tomatoes. These events were broadcast across Australia, and under pressure from public opinion, the council eventually reversed the ban on Aboriginal swimmers. The Freedom Ride then moved on, but on the way out they were followed by a line of cars, one of which collided with the rear of their bus forcing them to return to Moree where they found that the council had reneged on their previous decision. The Freedom Riders protested once again, forcing the council to  remove the ban once more.<ref name=Cockerill>{{cite web\n  | last =Cockerill\n  | first =Michael\n  | title =Australian football loses a trail-blazer\n  | publisher =[[FIFA]]\n  | date =20 April 2001\n  | url =http://images.fifa.com/en/organisation/index/0,1521,24227,00.html?articleid=24227\n  | accessdate =20 January 2007\n  | url-status =dead\n  | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20070312173606/http://images.fifa.com/en/organisation/index/0%2C1521%2C24227%2C00.html?articleid=24227\n  | archivedate =12 March 2007\n  | df =dmy-all\n  }}</ref>\n\nOn 6 August 1965, Charles Perkins staged a fake \"kidnapping\" of 5 year old Nancy Prasad from under the nose of immigration officials at the Sydney airport for the purpose of highlighting the injustice her deportation under Australia's \"White Australia\" immigration policy.<ref>{{ cite web|title=Immigration Nation: Part 3 | url =https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-WNRb8Hypjo }}</ref><ref name=telegraph-nancyprasad>{{cite news| url = http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/deported-nancy-prasad-was-the-little-girl-who-helped-bring-down-the-white-australia-policy/news-story/001ee3eff23d0cef94d0961e2811396a|title=Deported: Nancy Prasad was the little girl who helped bring down the White Australia policy|author=Benns, Matthew|work=Daily Telegraph|date=7 August 2015|access-date=16 December 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{ cite book|title =Deported: A History of Forced Departures from Australia  | first1 =Glenn|last1=Nicholls| url=https://books.google.com/?id=dRQcNtT35AIC&pg=PA113&dq=nancy+prasad#v=onepage&q=nancy%20prasad&f=false | isbn =9780868409894| year =2007}}</ref>  His antic had effect.  The newspapers headlined the \"kidnapping\".  Even so, 5 year old Nancy Prasad was taken to the airport again, and deported to Fiji on 7 August 1965.<ref name=telegraph-nancyprasad/>\n\n===1967 Referendum===\n{{See also|Australian referendum, 1967 (Aboriginals)}}\nIn 1967 a [[referendum]] was held on [[Australian Constitution|constitutional amendments]] to allow the inclusion of Aboriginal people in censuses and giving the [[Parliament of Australia]] the right to introduce legislation specifically for Aboriginal people. In the lead up to the referendum Perkins was manager of the Foundation for Aboriginal Affairs, an organization that took a key role in advocating a Yes vote. The constitutional amendment passed with a 90.77% majority.\n\n===Public service===\nIn 1969 Perkins began his career in public service as a Senior Research Officer with the Office of Aboriginal Affairs. In 1972, as a public servant, he was suspended for alleged improper conduct after he called the [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]]\u2013[[National Party of Australia|Country]] Coalition government in [[Western Australia]] 'racist and [[Redneck (stereotype)|redneck]]'.\n\nIn 1981, he was appointed Permanent Secretary of the [[Department of Aboriginal Affairs]], the first Aboriginal to become a permanent head of a federal government department. He served as Chairman of the Aboriginal Development Commission between 1981 and 1984. Throughout his career he was a strident critic of [[Government of Australia|Australian Government]] policies on indigenous affairs and was renowned for his fiery comments. [[Prime Minister of Australia|Prime Minister]] [[Bob Hawke]] once said of Perkins that he \"sometimes found it difficult to observe the constraints usually imposed on permanent heads of departments because he had a burning passion for advancing the interests of his people\". Perkins served as Secretary until 1988. A year later he became Chairman of the [[Arrernte Council]] of Central Australia.\n\nIn 1993 Perkins was elected commissioner of the [[Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Commission]] for an area of the central Northern Territory. In 1994, he was elected Deputy Chairperson of ATSIC.\n\n===Public commentary===\nOn 7 April 2000, Perkins suggested that 'Sydney will burn during the [Sydney 2000] Olympics.' The comment sparked outrage from many quarters.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.eniar.org/news/perkins.html | title=Charles Perkins \u2013 Obituary | publisher=The Times Magazine | work=[[The Times]] | date=20 August 2000 | accessdate=19 July 2008 | via=European Network for Indigenous Australian Rights | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421062414/http://www.eniar.org/news/perkins.html | archivedate=21 April 2012}}</ref> In May 2000 Perkins declared that the [[Australian Football League]] and the [[Australian Rugby League]] were racist, suggesting that the AFL \"acts in a racist manner at the highest level.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-26756419.html | title=AFL: Charles Perkins brands AFL and ARL as racist | date=24 May 2000 | agency=[[Australian Associated Press|AAP]] | accessdate=17 December 2008}}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n== Soccer career ==\nPerkins began playing in 1950 with Adelaide team the Yeeters [[Port Adelaide Pirates|Port Thistle]]. In 1951 he was selected for a [[South Australia]] under 18 representative team. He went on to play for a number of teams in Adelaide including International United (1954\u201355), Budapest (1956\u201357) and Fiorentina (1957).\n\nIn 1957 he was invited to trial with [[Football League First Division|English first division]] team [[Liverpool F.C.]]. Perkins ended up trialling and training with Liverpool's city rival [[Everton FC]]. While at Everton Perkins had a physical confrontation with the Everton reserve grade manager after being called a \"kangaroo bastard.\" After this incident, Perkins left Everton FC to move to Wigan where he worked as a coal miner at the [[Mosley Common]] Colliery alongside [[Great Britain national rugby league team|Great Britain]] [[rugby league]] player [[Terry O'Grady]]. Perkins played two seasons for leading English amateur team [[Bishop Auckland F.C.]] between 1957 and 1959.\nPerkins in mid-1959 decided to return to Australia after trialling with [[Manchester United]].<ref name=\"NLA\" />\n\nOn returning to Australia Perkins was appointed captain/coach of [[Adelaide Raiders|Adelaide Croatia]]. At Croatia he played alongside notable Aboriginal figures [[Gordon Briscoe]] and [[John Kundereri Moriarty|John Moriarty]].<ref name=\"Perkins\">{{cite interview | date=5 May 1998 | last=Perkins | first=Charles| interviewer=Robin Hughes |title=Charles Perkins - Tape2| work=Australian Biography}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title=The Australian People: An Encyclopedia of the Nation, Its People and Their Origins | publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] | last=Jupp | first=James | year=2001 | page=248 | isbn=0-521-80789-1}}</ref>\n\nIn 1961 when Perkins moved to Sydney to study at university he played with Pan-Hellenic (later known as [[Sydney Olympic FC]]) in the New South Wales State League where he became captain/coach. He later played for Bankstown and retired in 1965.\n\nHe later served as president of former [[National Soccer League]] team [[Canberra City SC|Canberra City]].  He was appointed Australian Soccer Federation (a forerunner of the [[Football Federation Australia]]) vice-president in 1987 and was the chairman of the Australian Indoor Soccer Federation (later known as the Australian Futsal Federation) for ten years until his death in [[Sydney]] in 2000.<ref name=Cockerill /><ref name=Perkins />\n\n==Awards and honours==\nPerkins was awarded Jaycees Young Man of the Year in 1966, [[NAIDOC]] Aboriginal of the Year in 1993 and an [[Officer of the Order of Australia]] in 1987.<ref name=Order/> Perkins was inducted into the [[Football Federation Australia Football Hall of Fame]] for services as a player, coach and administrator in 2000. In 1998 Perkins was awarded an honorary doctorate of letters by the [[University of Western Sydney]]. Shortly before his death he was awarded an honorary doctorate of law by the University of Sydney. Perkins was named by the [[National Trust of Australia]] as one of [[Australian National Living Treasures|Australia's Living National Treasures]].\n\nIn 2001 The Dr Charles Perkins AO Memorial Oration and Dr Charles Perkins AO Memorial Prize were established in his honour by the University of Sydney.  In 2009 The Charlie Perkins trust instituted two scholarships per year to allow indigenous Australians to study for up to three years at the [[University of Oxford]].<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/10/22/2721161.htm Funding for Indigenous Oxford scholarships (ABC News)]</ref><ref name=\"FFA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.footballhalloffame.com.au/ |title=The Australian Football Hall of Fame |publisher=[[Football Federation Australia]] |accessdate=9 December 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110107102858/http://www.footballhalloffame.com.au/ |archivedate=7 January 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=\"Uni\">{{cite web | url=http://www.koori.usyd.edu.au/news/oration.shtml | title=Dr Charles Perkins AO Annual Memorial Oration and Prize | publisher=[[University of Sydney]] | accessdate=18 December 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"trust\">{{cite web | url=http://www.nsw.nationaltrust.org.au/treasureslist.html | title=List of Treasures | publisher=[[National Trust of Australia|National Trust]] | accessdate=18 December 2008 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070210145542/http://www.nsw.nationaltrust.org.au/treasureslist.html | archivedate=10 February 2007 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012 [[The University of Sydney]] Centre for Obesity, Diabetes and Cardiovascular Disease was renamed the [[Charles Perkins Centre]] in his recognition.\n\n==Film and documentary==\n* 1993: ''[[Blood Brothers (film series)|Freedom Ride]]'' by Rachel Perkins, Ned R Lander \u2013 Australia \u2013 55 minutes<ref name=movie>{{cite web|url=http://www.creativespirits.info/resources/movies/FreedomRide.html|title=Aboriginal resources > Movies > Freedom Ride|access-date=23 May 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091125033645/http://www.creativespirits.info/resources/movies/FreedomRide.html|archive-date=25 November 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 2009: ''[[Fire Talker]]''\n* 2009: ''[[Remembering Charlie Perkins]]''  56 minutes 38 seconds\n\n===''Freedom Ride''===\n''Freedom Ride'' is part of a four-episode documentary by Rachel Perkins and Ned Lander. It tells a chapter of Charles Perkins' life. The Freedom Ride was a busload of concerned white and black people, most of them university students, who visited several towns in rural and outback Australia to elevate public awareness of racial intolerance in Australia.<ref name=movie/>\n\n==='' Fire Talker: The Life and Times of Charlie Perkins''===\nThis film by [[Ivan Sen]] uses archival footage from the early 1960s to 2001 and builds an intimate and honest portrait of Perkins life bound inexorably with the most dramatic political shifts in Australian Indigenous policy.<ref name=\"Sydney Operahouse\">{{cite press release | url=http://www.sydneyoperahouse.com/About/09EventMediaRelease/MessageSticks.aspx | title=Message Sticks, Australia's only Indigenous film festival celebrates its 10th anniversary | publisher=Sydney Opera House | accessdate=9 March 2015 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327102258/http://www.sydneyoperahouse.com/About/09EventMediaRelease/MessageSticks.aspx | archivedate=27 March 2012 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===''Remembering Charlie Perkins''===\n2009 Charlie Perkins memorial oration, [[Gordon Briscoe]] recalls Perkins' fight for equality and liberty.<ref name=\"brisco\">{{cite episode | title=Gordon Briscoe Remembers His Friend Charlie Perkins | series=Big Ideas | network=[[ABC News 24]] | airdate=6 November 2009 | url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/bigideas/browse/video_popup.htm?vidURL=/tv/bigideas/stories/2009/11/06/2734926-mediarss-full.xml&vidTitle=Gordon%20Briscoe%20Remembers%20His%20Friend%20Charlie%20Perkins&vidLength=Full | access-date=28 June 2019 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402202533/http://www.abc.net.au/tv/bigideas/browse/video_popup.htm?vidURL=%2Ftv%2Fbigideas%2Fstories%2F2009%2F11%2F06%2F2734926-mediarss-full.xml&vidTitle=Gordon%20Briscoe%20Remembers%20His%20Friend%20Charlie%20Perkins&vidLength=Full | archivedate=2 April 2015 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nPerkins died in Sydney on 19 October 2000 of [[renal failure]]. During the 1970s Perkins had a kidney transplant and at the time of his death was the longest post-transplant survivor in Australia.<ref name=\"NLA\" /><ref name=\"abc1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/pm/stories/s210963.htm|title=Hetty Perkins discusses kidney research fundraising|work=PM|publisher=ABC Radio|accessdate=8 October 2009}}</ref>  In the period immediately following his death, he was known as '''Kumantjayi Perkins''', Kumantjayi being a name used to refer to a deceased person in [[Arrernte people|Arrernte]] culture.<ref name=\"creative\">{{cite web | url=http://www.creativespirits.info/aboriginalculture/people/ | title=Should you name a dead Aboriginal person? | publisher=Creative Spirits, Jens Korff | accessdate=18 December 2008}}</ref> His body was returned to Alice Springs a week after his death.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading and external links==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book\n  | title =A Bastard like me\n  | last =Perkins\n  | first =Charles\n  | publisher =Ure Smith\n  | year =1975\n  | isbn =0-7254-0256-3 | location =Sydney\n  | authorlink =\n  }}\n*{{cite book\n  | title =Charles Perkins: a biography\n  | last =Read\n  | first =Peter\n  | publisher =Viking\n  | year =1990\n  | isbn =0-14-013280-5\n| location =Ringwood, Victoria\n  | authorlink =\n  }}\n*{{cite web\n |url=http://www.naa.gov.au/fsheets/fs225.html \n |title=Charles Nelson Perkins \n |date=July 2004 \n |publisher=[[National Archives of Australia]] \n |accessdate=20 January 2007 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060828174842/http://naa.gov.au/fsheets/fs225.html \n |archivedate=28 August 2006 \n |url-status=dead \n |df=dmy \n}}\n*{{cite web\n  | url =http://www.australianbiography.gov.au/subjects/perkins/\n  | title =Charles Perkins\n  | year =2004\n  | publisher =[[Government of Australia|Australian Government]]\n  | work =Australian Biography\n  | accessdate =  25 October 2010}}\n*Classroom resources on Charles Perkins: [http://dl.nfsa.gov.au/module/1026/ Institutions], [http://dl.nfsa.gov.au/module/1033/ Freedom Ride]\n*[http://www.perkinstrust.com.au/ The Charlie Perkins Trust for Children and Students]\n*[http://www.portrait.gov.au/people/charles-perkins-1936 Portraits of Charles Perkins] in the National Portrait Gallery \n{{refend}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{S-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Taylor (public servant)|John Taylor]] }}\n{{s-ttl|title= [[Departmental secretary|Secretary]] of the [[Department of Aboriginal Affairs]]| years   = 1984 \u2013 1988}}\n{{s-aft| after= [[Wilfred James \"Bill\" Gray|Bill Gray]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Football Federation Australia Hall of Fame}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perkins, Charles}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Alice Springs]]\n[[Category:Australian public servants]]\n[[Category:Australian soccer players]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriate soccer players]]\n[[Category:Indigenous Australian soccer players]]\n[[Category:Football Federation Australia Hall 